  "prompt": "Is division of states on the basis of religion, caste, ethnicity not good?",
  "response": "Dividing states based on religion, caste, or ethnicity is generally considered problematic for several reasons:\n\n1. Promotes Divisiveness\n- Creates artificial social barriers\n- Increases communal tensions\n- Undermines national unity\n\n2. Potential Negative Consequences\n- Can lead to discrimination\n- Might trigger social conflicts\n- Reduces opportunities for interaction between different groups\n\n3. Constitutional Principles\n- Goes against principles of secularism\n- Contradicts equality and fraternity\n- Promotes segregation instead of integration\n\n4. Long-term Social Impact\n- Weakens national identity\n- Hinders social cohesion\n- Perpetuates historical prejudices\n\n5. Economic Implications\n- Can create unequal development\n- Reduces economic opportunities\n- Limits resource sharing\n\n6. Democratic Values\n- Undermines democratic principles\n- Reduces representation of diverse perspectives\n- Restricts inclusive governance\n\n7. Alternative Approach\n- Focus on administrative efficiency\n- Promote inclusive development\n- Encourage inter-community dialogue\n\nWhile administrative reorganization might be necessary for effective governance, divisions should be based on administrative, geographical, and developmental considerations rather than identity-based factors.",
